When there are pre-generated meta data, this plugin can load them
directly to replay the functionality of the corresponding plugin. Currently,
it supports loading detection data in MOT detection format, and generates
meta data just like PGIE. This is useful to quickly replay and test the meta
data generated by external models.

Refer to the DeepStream SDK documentation for a description of the "nvreplay"
plugin.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pre-requisites:
- GStreamer-1.0 Development package
- GStreamer-1.0 Base Plugins Development package
- CUDA Runtime 10.0+
- yaml-cpp

Install gstreamer developement packages using:
   sudo apt-get install libgstreamer-plugins-base1.0-dev libgstreamer1.0-dev \
   libyaml-cpp-dev


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Compiling and installing the plugin:
Run make && sudo -E make install

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

As mentioned in https://motchallenge.net/, MOT detection format is a CSV format
where each line reprensets one detection. Each line structure is:
frame_num, track_id, left, top, width, height, confidence

For example:
1,1,100.5,200.3,50.2,80.1,0.95
1,2,300.0,150.0,60.0,90.0,0.88
...

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Corresponding config file changes (Add the following section) in DeepStream configs:
file-names should have the same order as source0, source1 ...
Assuming ground truth files are saved as:
<path>/labels/
    source0_detection.txt
    source1_detection.txt
    source2_detection.txt
    source3_detection.txt

deepstream-app config example:
[primary-gie]
enable=0

[replay]
enable=1
label-dir=<path>/labels/
file-names=source0_detection.txt;source1_detection.txt;source2_detection.txt;source3_detection.txt
max-frame-nums=100;100;100;100
label-width=1920
label-height=1080
interval=0

Nested folder structure is also supported. For example:
<path>/labels/
    source0/
        detection.txt
    source1/
        detection.txt
    source2/
        detection.txt
    source3/
        detection.txt

file-names=source0/detection.txt;source1/detection.txt;source2/detection.txt;source3/detection.txt

If label-width and label-height are not specified, they are 1920x1080
by default.

Interval is 0 by default. It is the number of batches skipped
when loading labels just like PGIE.

max-frame-nums specifies the max number of frames for each stream.
If not specified, it will be the max frame number in label files.